lopment of early Christian monasticism.Kim Haines-Eitzen draws on ancient monastic texts from Egypt, Sinai, and Palestine to explore how noise offered desert monks an opportunity to cultivate inner quietude, and shows how the desert quests of ancient monastics offer profound lessons for us about what it means to search for silence. Drawing on her own experiences making field recordings in the deserts of North America and Israel, she reveals how mountains, canyons, caves, rocky escarpments, and lush oases are deeply resonant places. Haines-Eitzen discusses how the desert is a place of paradoxes, both silent and noisy, pulling us toward contemplative isolation yet giving rise to vibrant collectives of fellow seekers.Accompanied by Haines-Eitzen’s evocative audio recordings of desert environments, Sonorous Desert reveals how desert sounds taught ancient monks about solitude, silence, and the life of community, and how they can help us understand ourselves if we slow down and listen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aDesertsxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aListeningxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aMonastic and religious lifexHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aSilencexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aSolitudexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Monasticism.2bisacsh  aAdmiration.  aAgave.  aAir pollution.  aAircraft.  aAmbience (sound recording).  aAnchorite.  aAnger.  aArchaeology.  aArches National Park.  aAsceticism.  aAsh Meadows National Wildlife Refuge.  aAthanasius of Alexandria.  aAudio engineer.  aBenedict of Nursia.  aBuddhism.  aCadillac Desert.  aCanyon.  aCello.  aChaplain.  aChiricahua Mountains.  aChiricahua National Monument.  aChristian History.  aChristian monasticism.  aChristian.  aCistercians.  aCockatiel.  aDecorum. 